                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.124A/54: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wharton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-09-22T22:00:00-00:44"
                            >September 22, 1929—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 23—8:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>51. Referring to your telegram No. 22, July 18, 5 p.m., and 26, July 24. Dr.
                    Allen Moore Walcott of Rockefeller Commission of Lagos arrived here 12th instant
                    for a survey of two or three weeks. No action has been taken Department’s
                    telegram No. 34, September 18 [<hi rend="italic">17</hi>], 10 a.m. [<hi
                        rend="italic">6 p.m.</hi>]</p>
                <p>He leaves me with impression that he will recommend to the Liberian Government
                    the appointment of a sanitary engineer who is United States public health
                    officer, bachelor in active condition, able to travel on foot. He is reluctant
                    to commit himself at this time, as here at the invitation of the Liberian
                    Government to make survey and recommendations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wharton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
